Title: Cron / Alerts Primer (status table, SLAs, and admin banner)

Purpose
- Track health of background jobs (cron / schedulers) in a DB table.
- Surface clear, admin-only alerts in the UI.
- Provide safe operations: dry-run, snapshots, and audit via Transactions.

Core Table (SQLite / SQLAlchemy-agnostic)
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS cron_status (
  job_name         TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  last_success_utc DATETIME,   -- UTC-naive
  last_error_utc   DATETIME,   -- UTC-naive
  last_error       TEXT        -- last exception / message
);

Recommended Indexes
- PRIMARY KEY(job_name) is enough for point lookups.
- (Optional) Add an audit table if you need history per run.

Update Contract (what each job must do)
On success:
  UPSERT(job_name) SET last_success_utc = NOW_UTC, last_error_utc = NULL, last_error = NULL
On failure:
  UPSERT(job_name) SET last_error_utc = NOW_UTC, last_error = "<exception or message>"

SQLite UPSERT Example
INSERT INTO cron_status (job_name, last_success_utc, last_error_utc, last_error)
VALUES (:job, :now, NULL, NULL)
ON CONFLICT(job_name) DO UPDATE SET
  last_success_utc = excluded.last_success_utc,
  last_error_utc   = NULL,
  last_error       = NULL;

…and for failure:
INSERT INTO cron_status (job_name, last_success_utc, last_error_utc, last_error)
VALUES (:job, NULL, :now, :err)
ON CONFLICT(job_name) DO UPDATE SET
  last_error_utc = excluded.last_error_utc,
  last_error     = excluded.last_error;

Python Helper (put in a tiny util module)
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from sqlalchemy import text
from app.extensions import db

def utcnow_naive():
    return datetime.now(timezone.utc).replace(tzinfo=None)

def cron_mark_success(job_name: str):
    db.session.execute(text("""
      INSERT INTO cron_status (job_name, last_success_utc, last_error_utc, last_error)
      VALUES (:job, :now, NULL, NULL)
      ON CONFLICT(job_name) DO UPDATE SET
        last_success_utc = excluded.last_success_utc,
        last_error_utc   = NULL,
        last_error       = NULL
    """), {"job": job_name, "now": utcnow_naive()})
    db.session.commit()

def cron_mark_failure(job_name: str, err_msg: str):
    db.session.execute(text("""
      INSERT INTO cron_status (job_name, last_success_utc, last_error_utc, last_error)
      VALUES (:job, NULL, :now, :err)
      ON CONFLICT(job_name) DO UPDATE SET
        last_error_utc = excluded.last_error_utc,
        last_error     = excluded.last_error
    """), {"job": job_name, "now": utcnow_naive(), "err": err_msg[:2000]})
    db.session.commit()

How a Job Should Report
try:
    # do work
    cron_mark_success("nightly-backup")
except Exception as e:
    cron_mark_failure("nightly-backup", str(e))
    raise  # let your scheduler re-try / backoff as configured

Service Level Expectations (SLAs)
- Choose a staleness window per job class:
  • High-frequency (every 5–15 min): stale if > 1 hour
  • Daily jobs: stale if > 36 hours (default used by banner)
  • Weekly jobs: stale if > 10 days
- You can store per-job SLA in a small JSON policy (e.g., governance key cron.sla_hours) if needs differ.

Admin-Only Alert Banner (UI)
- Banner renders ONLY for admins (see user_is_admin()).
- “Stale” if job has NO last_success_utc or it is older than SLA window.
- “Error” if last_error is non-empty (show timestamp + brief message).
- Current default window: 36 hours.

Example Jinja Context (already wired)
alerts = []
cutoff = now_utc - timedelta(hours=36)
for row in cron_status:
  if row.last_error:
    alerts.append(f"{row.job_name} error at {row.last_error_utc}: {row.last_error}")
  elif not row.last_success_utc or row.last_success_utc < cutoff:
    alerts.append(f"{row.job_name} is stale; no success in 36h.")

Admin Tools (recommended buttons)
- Verify jobs: show table with job_name, last_success_utc, last_error_utc, last_error.
- “Acknowledge” last error (optional): clears last_error but leaves last_error_utc (use sparingly).
- Run-now / Trigger (optional hook): invoke a safe endpoint to enqueue the job (must be CSRF+admin protected).
- Snapshot DB (existing button) before any destructive job (e.g., compaction).

Audit via Transactions
- When Admin triggers “Run-now” or “Acknowledge”, emit an event:
  type="cron.job.triggered" / "cron.job.acknowledged"
  slice="admin"
  refs={"job_name": "...", "action": "..."}
- The job’s own success/failure is not ledgered by default (status table is enough). If needed, you can add a separate “cron.job.finished” event.

CLI / Script Checks
- List status:
  SELECT * FROM cron_status ORDER BY job_name;
- Stale count (36h):
  SELECT COUNT(*) FROM cron_status
    WHERE last_success_utc IS NULL
       OR last_success_utc < DATETIME('now', '-36 hours');
- Clear an error (manual):
  UPDATE cron_status SET last_error=NULL WHERE job_name=:job;

Common Pitfalls
- Not committing the UPSERT (job exits early → no status change).
- Timezone drift: always store UTC-naive, compare to UTC-naive now().
- Unbounded error strings: truncate to a safe length (2–4KB).
- Running banner for non-admins: keep the banner admin-only.

Backoff & Retries (operational note)
- Let your scheduler (cron/systemd/celery) handle exponential backoff.
- Jobs must still record failure immediately so the banner surfaces it.

Retention / Cleanup
- cron_status stores only the latest state per job (no growth).
- If you keep a history table, prune with a weekly job (e.g., keep 90 days).

